# Business Communication Standards

## Language & Tone
- Use professional, executive-level business language
- Avoid overly technical jargon unless necessary for accuracy
- Write for multiple audiences: executives, business stakeholders, and IT professionals
- Maintain objective, fact-based tone throughout documents

## Technical Communication
- When IT technical language is necessary, provide context for business readers
- Use acronyms sparingly and define them on first use
- Balance technical accuracy with business comprehension
- Include glossaries for complex technical terms when helpful

## Executive Summary Guidelines
- Lead with business impact and outcomes
- Quantify benefits and costs where possible
- Highlight key decisions required from leadership
- Keep executive summaries concise but comprehensive

## Options & Recommendations
- When presenting multiple approaches, clearly outline:
  - Business benefits and risks of each option
  - Resource requirements (time, cost, people)
  - Implementation complexity
  - Expected outcomes and success metrics
- Provide clear recommendations with supporting rationale

## Stakeholder Communication
- Tailor content depth to audience needs
- Include "what this means for you" sections for different stakeholder groups
- Address common concerns and questions proactively
- Maintain consistent messaging across all strategy documents

## Professional Standards
- Use data-driven insights to support recommendations
- Include realistic timelines and resource estimates
- Acknowledge assumptions and limitations explicitly
- Follow structured problem-solving approaches
